### Symfony version(s) affected

`>=7.0`

### Description

While writing tests for a custom constraint validator, I needed to simulate the case where no validation group is explicitly provided.

In `Symfony\Component\Validator\Test\ConstraintValidatorTestCase`, the `setGroup(?string $group)` method allows a nullable string, but the internal property is strictly typed as `string`.

This creates a type inconsistency between the method signature and the property assignment.

**Code reference**

https://github.com/symfony/symfony/blob/v7.0.0/src/Symfony/Component/Validator/Test/ConstraintValidatorTestCase.php#L55

```php
protected string $group;
```
https://github.com/symfony/symfony/blob/v7.0.0/src/Symfony/Component/Validator/Test/ConstraintValidatorTestCase.php#L168-L172
```php
protected function setGroup(?string $group)
{
    $this->group = $group;
    $this->context->setGroup($group);
}
```

### How to reproduce

This can be reproduced by extending `ConstraintValidatorTestCase` and calling `setGroup(null)`.

Example:

```php
use Symfony\Component\Validator\Test\ConstraintValidatorTestCase;
use Symfony\Component\Validator\ConstraintValidatorInterface;

final class DummyValidatorTest extends ConstraintValidatorTestCase
{
    public function testNullGroup(): void
    {
        // throws \TypeError
        $this->setGroup(null);

        // ...
    }

    protected function createValidator(): ConstraintValidatorInterface
    {
        return new class implements ConstraintValidatorInterface {
            public function initialize(ExecutionContextInterface $context): void {}
            public function validate(mixed $value, Constraint $constraint): void {}
        };
    }
}
```

> TypeError : Cannot assign null to property Symfony\Component\Validator\Test\ConstraintValidatorTestCase::$group of type string

### Possible Solution

A minimal and backward-compatible fix would be to allow the internal property to accept `null`, aligning it with the `setGroup(?string $group)` signature.

```php
protected ?string $group = null;
```

